  "theory": {
    "overview": "Solutions are homogeneous mixtures where one substance (solute) is dissolved in another (solvent). They can exist in any combination of solid, liquid, and gas states. Concentration quantifies the amount of solute present.",
    "keyPoints": [
      "A solution must be homogeneous throughout.",
      "There are 8 types of solutions based on physical states.",
      "Mass percentage is a common way to express concentration."
    ],
    "detailedContent": "Solutions differ from heterogeneous mixtures because the particles are uniformly distributed at the molecular level. The solute is the minor component, and the solvent is the major one. For example, in brass (an alloy), zinc dissolves in copper. In soda water, carbon dioxide gas dissolves under pressure in liquid water. When calculating concentration, Mass % = (Mass of Solute / Total Mass of Solution) * 100. This method is preferred for solids because mass does not change with temperature."
